{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"62e6f846-3ee4-4e46-9b8a-0f6240f6b2b1","content":"Add a `.vscode/mcp.json` file to your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `type: \"stdio\"` means Copilot communicates with your server via stdin/stdout.\n- `command`/`args` launch your server — adjust the path if your workspace root differs.\n- Once saved, VS Code will detect the server automatically in agent mode (Copilot Chat → Agent).\n\nIf your server needs environment variables, add an `\"env\"` block:\n\n```json\n\"env\": { \"MY_VAR\": \"value\" }\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"514408e8-5523-47bd-ac98-849c992aa92d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to configure `mcp.json` to use their C# MCP server with GitHub Copilot in VS Code agent mode. Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of VS Code MCP configuration.","outputTokens":275,"requestId":"2C07:2E6F9:2A9CF8B:2EFA62F:69FD367A"},"id":"45ff1718-a4ae-4d59-941c-902ca6ad84b4","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:04:01.776Z","parentId":"a4183a93-0823-492e-8e46-bd1a31ca5c56"}
